    "Exercises": {
      "concept_checks": [
        "Q1: Explain why central differencing schemes can produce oscillations in two-phase flow",
        "Q2: Compare the accuracy and stability characteristics of upwind vs linearUpwind schemes",
        "Q3: Why are TVD schemes particularly important for two-phase flow simulations?",
        "Q4: Given a two-phase flow with sharp interfaces, which scheme would you select and why?"
      ],
      "answers": [
        "A1: Central schemes have no directional bias and can produce unphysical oscillations near discontinuities like phase interfaces",
        "A2: Upwind is first-order accurate and unconditionally stable but highly diffusive. LinearUpwind is second-order accurate with less diffusion but conditionally stable",
        "A3: TVD schemes maintain monotonicity while achieving higher order accuracy, preventing overshoots/undershoots at phase interfaces",
        "A4: A TVD scheme like vanLeer or MUSCL would be optimal for balancing accuracy, stability, and boundedness at sharp interfaces"
      ]
    }
